00:13:14,083 --> 00:13:15,750
or bring in a composite artist.

258
00:13:15,833 --> 00:13:18,083
Needless to say we
tried both methods.

259
00:13:19,375 --> 00:13:21,250
And it sounds
like neither worked.

260
00:13:21,333 --> 00:13:22,750
No.

261
00:13:22,833 --> 00:13:24,250
So we're back to square one.

262
00:13:24,333 --> 00:13:28,500
Our only image is a blurry
photo Sasayama took years ago.

263
00:13:38,375 --> 00:13:39,791
Did you at least get
something out of it?

264
00:13:39,875 --> 00:13:41,541
Yes! Of course!

265
00:13:41,625 --> 00:13:43,583
He's a fantastic teacher.

266
00:13:43,666 --> 00:13:45,625
In fact, I don't
get why his lectures

267
00:13:45,708 --> 00:13:47,875
aren't in the MWPSB archives?

268
00:13:47,958 --> 00:13:50,125
They would never do that.

269
00:13:50,208 --> 00:13:52,625
What's the real story with him?

270
00:13:52,708 --> 00:13:54,916
It was back when the
University System

271
00:13:55,000 --> 00:13:57,750
still existed alongside
the Sybil System.

272
00:13:57,833 --> 00:14:00,000
Saiga's criminology courses

273
00:14:00,083 --> 00:14:03,000
were specifically set up
to train investigators.

274
00:14:03,083 --> 00:14:06,541
But one day they
found a big problem.

275
00:14:06,625 --> 00:14:09,916
The hues of his
students became clouded,

276
00:14:10,000 --> 00:14:13,291
and their Crime Coefficients
saw a big jump.

277
00:14:13,708 --> 00:14:15,666
Relax, not for every student.

278
00:14:15,750 --> 00:14:19,750
One-on-one lectures
like yours today are fine.

279
00:14:19,833 --> 00:14:22,958
And besides, your Hue's
impossible to cloud anyway.

280
00:14:23,041 --> 00:14:24,416
Yeah, but, to think listening

281
00:14:24,500 --> 00:14:27,666
to a guy speak could raise
your Crime Coefficient.

282
00:14:28,208 --> 00:14:31,250
Say there's a dark swamp,
and you can't see the bottom.

283
00:14:31,333 --> 00:14:35,666
If you want to know what's
down there, you gotta jump.

284
00:14:35,750 --> 00:14:36,916
Mister Saiga can handle it,

285
00:14:37,000 --> 00:14:39,416
because he swims
down there all the time.

286
00:14:39,500 --> 00:14:42,125
But for most of his students,
it's a new experience,

287
00:14:42,208 --> 00:14:45,291
and they can't
always surface safely.

288
00:14:45,375 --> 00:14:47,791
They can't handle
what's in the swamp.

289
00:14:49,791 --> 00:14:51,375
You seem like someone
who could dive in,

290
00:14:51,458 --> 00:14:54,125
touch the bottom and come
back without a scratch.

291
00:14:54,208 --> 00:14:54,916
Thanks.

292
00:14:55,000 --> 00:14:56,541
But I doubt that.

293
00:14:56,625 --> 00:14:59,250
If you were to ask our dear
friend the Sibyl System,

294
00:14:59,333 --> 00:15:01,833
I'd hit the black mud
and never come back.

295
00:15:04,375 --> 00:15:06,708
What kind of animal do you
think is the most cunning,

296
00:15:06,791 --> 00:15:08,875
and has the lowest
risk of going extinct,

297
00:15:08,958 --> 00:15:11,458
no matter how many
are hunted and killed?

298
00:15:11,541 --> 00:15:13,416
That can only be Man.

299
00:15:13,500 --> 00:15:15,166
That was too easy for you.

300
00:15:16,625 --> 00:15:18,291
Nowadays

301
00:15:18,375 --> 00:15:22,458
It's hard for the common citizen
to get a hunting license.

302
00:15:26,416 --> 00:15:29,208
Makishima I appreciate,
your company.

303
00:15:40,125 --> 00:15:41,458
That pipe of yours...

304
00:15:41,541 --> 00:15:43,375
That's not ivory, is it?

305
00:15:43,458 --> 00:15:45,500
I suppose I haven't
shown it to you yet.

306
00:15:45,583 --> 00:15:46,750
Excluding the mouthpiece,

307
00:15:46,833 --> 00:15:50,083
this pipe is made from
Rikako Ouryou's bones.

308
00:15:50,750 --> 00:15:51,625
Oh.

309
00:15:51,708 --> 00:15:54,125
When I inhale it like this...

310
00:15:56,416 --> 00:15:58,833
My mind feels as sharp
as a young man's again.

311
00:16:01,333 --> 00:16:04,083
It's like I'm breathing in
the souls of my terrified prey,

312
00:16:04,166 --> 00:16:06,833
so that I might feast upon
their life-giving energy.

313
00:16:08,458 --> 00:16:10,958
Obviously, you've overcome
your body's aging.

314
00:16:11,041 --> 00:16:13,666
Your only worry
left is your mind.

315
00:16:13,750 --> 00:16:15,291
That's exactly correct.

316
00:16:15,375 --> 00:16:19,541
To maintain a healthy mind and
body requires some sacrifices.

317
00:16:21,375 --> 00:16:23,791
Particularly, the
lives of others.

318
00:16:24,416 --> 00:16:26,666
Unfortunately, many of
those seeking eternal life,

319
00:16:26,750 --> 00:16:28,333
neglect feeding their minds

320
00:16:28,416 --> 00:16:30,583
in favor of keeping
their bodies young.

321
00:16:30,666 --> 00:16:34,458
This has one result: A long
life, as beautiful zombies.

322
00:16:34,541 --> 00:16:36,916
It's a rather foolish
end, don't you think?

323
00:16:37,000 --> 00:16:38,958
The thrill you get
from a successful hunt

324
00:16:39,041 --> 00:16:42,416
It's like a reward for
coming face to face

325
00:16:42,500 --> 00:16:44,291
with death and surviving.

326
00:16:44,375 --> 00:16:45,541
You're quite right.

327
00:16:45,625 --> 00:16:47,500
In hunting, the more
dangerous your prey,

328
00:16:47,583 --> 00:16:50,666
the more potent the stimulation
your brain gets from killing it.

329
00:16:50,750 --> 00:16:52,333
Then I have good news for you.

330
00:16:52,416 --> 00:16:53,583
I think I can arrange

331
00:16:53,666 --> 00:16:55,833
for your next prey to
be the most potent yet.

332
00:16:55,916 --> 00:16:57,250
Go on.

333
00:16:59,166 --> 00:17:01,083
He's an Enforcer.

334
00:17:01,166 --> 00:17:03,208
How intriguing.

335
00:17:03,291 --> 00:17:05,333
His name is...

336
00:17:05,416 --> 00:17:06,458
So much for that.

337
00:17:06,541 --> 00:17:07,666
I thought for sure
we'd find something

338
00:17:07,750 --> 00:17:09,541
in his lecture attendee list.

339
00:17:09,625 --> 00:17:10,583
That's how it goes

340
00:17:10,666 --> 00:17:12,500
But as long as
Makishima's alive,

341
00:17:12,583 --> 00:17:15,375
he must be leaving
some kind of trail.

342
00:17:21,583 --> 00:17:22,958
I heard you took
Inspector Tsunemori

343
00:17:23,041 --> 00:17:25,125
to meet with Jouji Saiga today.

344
00:17:25,208 --> 00:17:26,208
Yeah.

345
00:17:26,291 --> 00:17:28,333
I asked Kogami to
take me there, sir

346
00:17:28,416 --> 00:17:29,583
What're you thinking, Kogami?

347
00:17:29,666 --> 00:17:31,500
Trying to drag her
down into the mud?

348
00:17:31,583 --> 00:17:32,916
Make her someone
who gives it all up

349
00:17:33,000 --> 00:17:34,875
to be a latent
criminal like you?

350
00:17:34,958 --> 00:17:36,166
Hey, that's not true!

351
00:17:36,250 --> 00:17:37,958
And I don't want you
treating me like a child!

352
00:17:38,041 --> 00:17:41,500
That is exactly what you are!
A clueless naive child!!

353
00:17:43,791 --> 00:17:45,458
Why do you think we have
different classifications

354
00:17:45,541 --> 00:17:46,958
for Inspectors and Enforcers?

355
00:17:47,041 --> 00:17:49,375
It's to lower the risk of a
healthy person's Psycho-Pass

356
00:17:49,458 --> 00:17:52,250
becoming clouded during
a criminal investigation.

357
00:17:52,333 --> 00:17:53,750
We have latent criminals,

358
00:17:53,833 --> 00:17:56,833
with no hope of returning
to society do our dirty work.

359
00:17:56,916 --> 00:17:58,166
That way, Inspector,

360
00:17:58,250 --> 00:18:00,416
you can fulfill your duty
and protect your mind.

361
00:18:00,500 --> 00:18:02,041
That doesn't sound
like teamwork!

362
00:18:02,125 --> 00:18:03,208
Is our job to solve crimes,

363
00:18:03,291 --> 00:18:05,500
or to protect our
own Psycho-Passes?

364
00:18:05,583 --> 00:18:07,958
Just tell me what's
important, so I know!

365
00:18:08,041 --> 00:18:10,333
Akane, are you trying
to throw away your career?

366
00:18:10,416 --> 00:18:14,041
You're gonna sacrifice
everything you've built so far?

367
00:18:14,125 --> 00:18:14,916
For what!

368
00:18:15,000 --> 00:18:17,458
Sir, it's...

369
00:18:18,791 --> 00:18:20,583
It's true that I'm a rookie!

370
00:18:20,666 --> 00:18:23,083
And I do have great
respect for your seniority!

371
00:18:23,166 --> 00:18:25,166
But don't forget,
I am still an Inspector,

372
00:18:25,250 --> 00:18:28,291
and we are on equal
footing in terms of rank.

373
00:18:28,875 --> 00:18:31,208
I can manage my Hue
just fine, thank you!

374
00:18:31,291 --> 00:18:32,875
Just 'cause you're my senior
doesn't give you the right

375
00:18:32,958 --> 00:18:34,750
to keep embarrassing
me in the workplace,

376
00:18:34,833 --> 00:18:36,458
or to question my Psycho-Pass

377
00:18:36,541 --> 00:18:39,291
and abilities in
front of our Enforcers.

378
00:18:46,250 --> 00:18:48,041
I can't believe his nerve!

379
00:18:52,291 --> 00:18:53,666
Whoa, where are you going?

380
00:18:53,750 --> 00:18:55,416
To file a complaint
with the bureau chief.

381
00:18:55,500 --> 00:18:57,750
Any chance you'll let me
talk ya outta that, Missy?

382
00:18:57,833 --> 00:18:59,083
Try.

383
00:19:09,583 --> 00:19:12,916
Ginoza's father, well, poor
guy's a latent criminal.

384
00:19:13,000 --> 00:19:14,833
What?

385
00:19:14,916 --> 00:19:16,791
Ginoza was a little
kid when they first

386
00:19:16,875 --> 00:19:19,208
put the Sibyl System
into operation.

387
00:19:19,291 --> 00:19:21,791
In those early days, rumors
about latent criminals spread

388
00:19:21,875 --> 00:19:26,791
around the country like
wildfire, causing mass panic.

389
00:19:26,875 --> 00:19:28,708
If anyone showed a
high Crime Coefficient

390
00:19:28,791 --> 00:19:31,041
that was enough for the
whole family to get treated

391
00:19:31,125 --> 00:19:33,833
as if they were
all latent criminals.

392
00:19:37,458 --> 00:19:38,500
Can't imagine being a kid

393
00:19:38,583 --> 00:19:40,833
and going through
something like that.

394
00:19:40,916 --> 00:19:44,375
When a detective
immerses himself in a case,

395
00:19:44,458 --> 00:19:46,208
sooner or later the Sibyl System

396
00:19:46,291 --> 00:19:49,541
will start keeping
an eye on him, too.

397
00:19:49,625 --> 00:19:52,333
Most think of criminals
and cops as opposites

398
00:19:52,416 --> 00:19:54,666
but they're actually
on the same wave.

399
00:19:54,750 --> 00:19:55,916
Now we've got the
Enforcer and Inspector

400
00:19:56,000 --> 00:19:58,333
arrangement to minimize risk,

401
00:19:58,416 --> 00:20:00,375
but in the early days,
many detectives

402
00:20:00,458 --> 00:20:04,750
saw themselves classified
as latent criminals.

403
00:20:04,833 --> 00:20:08,791
Ginoza's Dad was one of
those unlucky detectives.

404
00:20:08,875 --> 00:20:10,666
I never knew that.

405
00:20:10,750 --> 00:20:12,708
This is why he comes
down so hard on those

406
00:20:12,791 --> 00:20:16,041
he thinks are unnecessarily
risking their Hues.

407
00:20:16,125 --> 00:20:18,333
It happened with his
old partner, Kogami.

408
00:20:18,416 --> 00:20:19,916
Yes, I'm aware.

409
00:20:20,000 --> 00:20:22,166
Ginoza feels he was betrayed
twice.

410
00:20:22,250 --> 00:20:24,833
First by his father,
then by his best friend.

411
00:20:24,916 --> 00:20:27,208
This is why he acts the
way he does toward you.

412
00:20:27,291 --> 00:20:29,375
He doesn't want it
to ever happen again.

413
00:20:29,458 --> 00:20:30,875
But does he have to be a jerk?

414
00:20:30,958 --> 00:20:32,666
No, you're right. He doesn't.

415
00:20:32,750 --> 00:20:37,166
But, Missy you got lotsa friends
and family back home, don't ya?

416
00:20:41,333 --> 00:20:43,750
Times have changed some,
but one thing's certain:

417
00:20:43,833 --> 00:20:46,000
if your Psycho-Pass
ever comes up clouded,

418
00:20:46,083 --> 00:20:49,208
the people you care
about will still stuffer.

419
00:20:49,291 --> 00:20:50,625
That's why we
Enforcers are here.

420
00:20:50,708 --> 00:20:52,458
To help ya avoid that.

421
00:20:54,333 --> 00:20:56,083
Does Mister Kogami
see his Enforcer job

422
00:20:56,166 --> 00:20:58,333
the same way that you do?

423
00:20:58,416 --> 00:21:00,250
He used to.

424
00:21:00,333 --> 00:21:02,541
But now, I don't know...

425
00:21:04,875 --> 00:21:06,041
I don't think he
cares about anything

426
00:21:06,125 --> 00:21:10,000
beyond finding Makishima
and getting his revenge.

427
00:21:11,250 --> 00:21:13,833
I'm afraid I won't
capture him alive.

428
00:21:13,916 --> 00:21:15,750
Is that okay?

429
00:21:15,833 --> 00:21:17,166
Why yes of course.

430
00:21:17,250 --> 00:21:19,916
I expect nothing less from you.

431
00:21:20,000 --> 00:21:23,250
I should mention something
I don't think you've noticed.

432
00:21:23,333 --> 00:21:27,375
Shinya Kogami, whenever you
mention him in conversation...

433
00:21:27,458 --> 00:21:30,625
You get such an amused
look on your face.

